SIMPLE: whet
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whet
<hw>Whet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Whetted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Whetting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>hwettan</ets>; akin to
D. <ets>wetten</ets>, G. <ets>wetzen</ets>, OHG. <ets>wezzen</ets>,
Icel. <ets>hvetja</ets>, Sw. <ets>v⟦aum⟧ttja</ets>, and AS.
<ets>hw⟦ae⟧t</ets> vigorous, brave, OS. <ets>hwat</ets>, OHG.
<ets>waz</ets>, <ets>was</ets>, sharp, Icel. <ets>hvatr</ets>, bold,
active, Sw. <ets>hvass</ets> sharp, Dan. <ets>hvas</ets>, Goth.
<ets>hwassaba</ets> sharply, and probably to Skr. <ets>cud</ets> to
impel, urge on.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To rub or on with some substance, as a piece of
stone, for the purpose of sharpening; to sharpen by attrition; <as>as,
to <ex>whet</ex> a knife</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mower <qex>whets</qex> his scythe.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here roams the wolf, the eagle <qex>whets</qex> his beak.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make sharp, keen, or eager; to excite; to
stimulate; <as>as, to <ex>whet</ex> the appetite or the
courage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Since Cassius first did <qex>whet</qex> me against Caesar,⟦br⟧
I have not slept.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To whet on</b></col>, <col><b>To whet
forward</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to urge on or forward; to instigate.</cd>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Whet
<hw>Whet</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of whetting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which whets or sharpens; esp., an
appetizer.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Sips, drams, and <xex>whets</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Whet slate</b></col> <fld>(Min.)</fld>, <cd>a variety of
slate used for sharpening cutting instruments; novaculite; -- called
also <altname>whetstone slate</altname>, and
<altname>oilstone</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whether</ent>⟦br⟧
